\subsubsection*{Summary}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Executive Summary}
This empirical study evaluates the comparative predictive performance of linear regression and generalized additive models (GAMs) in residential real estate valuation using a dataset of 522 transactions. Diagnostic analyses revealed substantial violations of linear regression assumptions, including non-normality (Shapiro-Wilk $W=0.937$, $p<0.001$) and heteroscedasticity (Breusch-Pagan $\chi^2=147.25$, $p<0.001$). While logarithmic transformation (optimal $\lambda=-0.195$) improved model fit ($R^2=0.834$ vs. $0.829$ in linear form), residual diagnostics indicated persistent assumption violations. GAMs demonstrated superior predictive accuracy, particularly for capturing non-linear relationships, achieving lower root mean square error values ($\text{RMSE}=0.0194$ for square footage vs. $0.0206$ in log-linear models) and explaining $83.5\%$ of price variance. Cross-validation results confirmed GAMs' enhanced stability ($\text{SD}$ of $R^2=0.015$ vs. $0.052$ for linear models). The analysis identifies square footage ($\beta=101.8$, $p<0.001$) and construction quality ($\Delta\text{RMSE}=-0.001$) as the most influential predictors.These findings suggest GAMs should be prioritized for accurate valuation in contexts requiring predictive precision, while acknowledging linear models retain utility for their interpretability in exploratory analyses. 

